questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;The following sentence has been divided into parts. One of them may contain an error.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Select the part that contains the error from the given options. If you don&amp;#39;t find any error, mark &amp;#39;No error&amp;#39; as your answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He has been (1) watered the plants (2) for one hour. (3) No error&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the past participle &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;watered&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; instead of the present participle &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;watering&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; following &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;has been&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct construction here should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;has been watering&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to indicate a continuous action.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 2&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;He has been &lt;strong&gt;watering the plants&lt;/strong&gt; for one hour.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1: &amp;quot;He has been&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3: &amp;quot;for one hour.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;No error&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in part 2.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;I tried hardly to teach her&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the sentence is with the usage of &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;hardly&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Hardly&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; means barely or scarcely and is not the adverb form of &amp;#39;hard&amp;#39;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct word to use here is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;hard&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;, which means &lt;strong&gt;with a great deal of effort.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the sentence should be &amp;quot;I tried &lt;strong&gt;hard &lt;/strong&gt;to teach her my sign language, but she was dull and lazy.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This sentence implies that the speaker made a significant effort to teach the other person sign language, but the person was not responsive.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The following sentence has been divided into parts. One of them may contain an&amp;nbsp;error. Select the part that contains the error from the given options. If you don&amp;rsquo;t find&amp;nbsp;any error, mark &amp;lsquo;No error&amp;rsquo; as your answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This is our third reminder (A)/ and we are much surprised (B)/ at receiving no answer from you. (C)/ No error (D).

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;and we are much surprised&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;much surprised&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;in&lt;strong&gt; Part B &lt;/strong&gt;of the sentence. While &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;much&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is &lt;strong&gt;an adverb&lt;/strong&gt; used to intensify &lt;strong&gt;adjectives&lt;/strong&gt; or other &lt;strong&gt;adverbs&lt;/strong&gt; in some cases, it&amp;#39;s not commonly used with the adjective &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;surprised&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; in modern English. Instead, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;very&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;quite&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; would be more suitable to emphasize the degree of surprise.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Here&amp;#39;s a breakdown:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Incorrect: This is our third reminder and we are &lt;strong&gt;much&lt;/strong&gt; surprised at receiving no answer from you.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Correct: This is our third reminder and we are &lt;strong&gt;very &lt;/strong&gt;surprised at receiving no answer from you.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Very&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; fits more naturally in this context &lt;strong&gt;to express a high degree of surprise&lt;/strong&gt; regarding &lt;strong&gt;the lack of response.&lt;/strong&gt; It&amp;#39;s a matter of &lt;strong&gt;idiomatic&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;usage&lt;/strong&gt; where &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;very&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; aligns better with the &lt;strong&gt;adjective&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;surprised&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;This is our third reminder &lt;strong&gt;and we are very surprised&lt;/strong&gt; at receiving no answer from you.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;1&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the first part of the sentence. The phrase &amp;quot;Making and to get rid of&amp;quot; is grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the incorrect use of the infinitive form &amp;quot;to get rid of&amp;quot; after the conjunction &amp;quot;and&amp;quot;. When two verbs are joined by &amp;quot;and&amp;quot;, they need to be in the same form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the corrected phrase should be &amp;quot;Making and getting rid of&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the corrected sentence should be: &amp;quot;Making and getting rid of excess food accounts for around 8-10 percent of greenhouse gas emissions.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;2&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;is arguably more significant than any technological innovation&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the part of the sentence: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;is arguably more significant than any technological innovation.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase incorrectly suggests that the internal combustion engine is more significant than all technological innovations, which is factually incorrect and also grammatically ambiguous.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct phrasing should align with the intended comparative context, maintaining clarity and logical meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The internal combustion engine&amp;rsquo;s contribution to atmospheric carbon dioxide levels &lt;strong&gt;is arguably more significant than any other&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;technological innovation&amp;nbsp;of the industrial era&lt;/strong&gt;, with the possible exception of the coal-fired steam engine&amp;nbsp;which powered the initial expansion of the global manufacturing sector.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Comparative Structures:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure:&lt;/strong&gt; X is more significant than Y.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The internet is more influential than television in today&amp;rsquo;s world.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Usage:&lt;/strong&gt; Used to compare two entities or ideas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Modifiers:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Words like &amp;quot;arguably&amp;quot; are used to make claims less absolute.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Correct placement of such words ensures clarity and precision in meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;(a) Ram or Hari must lend his hand.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(b)&amp;nbsp;He and myself were working together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(c) None but the brave deserves the fair.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Identify the &lt;strong&gt;correct &lt;/strong&gt;sentence/s.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Only (a) and (c)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(a) Ram or Hari must lend his hand. - This sentence is grammatically &lt;strong&gt;correct&lt;/strong&gt;. It uses the pronoun &amp;quot;his&amp;quot; to refer to &amp;quot;Ram or Hari,&amp;quot; which is singular. When two or more singular nouns or pronouns are connected by or or nor, use a singular verb. The book or the pen is in the drawer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(b) He and myself were working together. - This sentence is grammatically &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt;. The use of &amp;quot;myself&amp;quot; as a subject pronoun is not appropriate here. It should be &amp;quot;He and I were working together.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(c) None but the brave deserves the fair. - This sentence is grammatically &lt;strong&gt;correct&lt;/strong&gt;. It follows subject-verb agreement and is a valid sentence structure.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct option is&lt;strong&gt; 1) Only (a) and (c).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;shall be playing&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The error in the sentence is the use of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;shall be&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; in place of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;will be&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In modern usage, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;will&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is more commonly used than &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;shall&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;I will be playing for four hours&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;I&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt; will be playing &lt;/span&gt;for four hours.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;four hours&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;This part of the sentence is correct. It appropriately specifies the duration.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I&lt;/strong&gt;: This part of the sentence is correct. It is the subject pronoun.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;This part of the sentence is correct. It is the correct preposition to indicate duration.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Here, the erroneous part is-&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(D)&amp;#39;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;part (D)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;one of those&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is talking about a plural subject&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;(people in this case), it takes a plural verb.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;don&amp;#39;t&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is used when speaking in the first and second person plural and singular and the third person plural &lt;strong&gt;(&amp;quot;I,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;you,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;we,&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;they&amp;quot;)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Doesn&amp;#39;t&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is used when speaking in the third person singular only (&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;he,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;she,&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;it&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​​To make the sentence grammatically correct, we must substitute&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;doesn&amp;#39;t&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;with&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;don&amp;#39;t.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;My father is one of those people who &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;don&amp;#39;t like&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;football.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;this part of the sentence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;has an error&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the fourth part of the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;past tense of the verb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;lead&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct past tense form should be&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;led.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;correct form of the verb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;led&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;in place of&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;lead&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The rabbit led the boy towards the outskirts of the city.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &amp;#39;lead&amp;#39; is present tense, and its past tense form is &amp;#39;led&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using the correct verb tense is crucial for maintaining the proper time reference in a sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Reviewing subject-verb agreement and verb tenses can help avoid such common mistakes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Which of the following sentences is/are grammatically correct among the three given below?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A.&amp;nbsp;The scenery of Kashmir are enchanting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B.&amp;nbsp;Ethics deals with moral conduct.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C.&amp;nbsp;There was great applause when the speaker sat down.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Only B and C&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The error here lies in the &lt;strong&gt;Subject-Verb agreement&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Let&amp;#39;s look at the options given:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Statement A:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;Some nouns always take a singular verb.&amp;nbsp;In this given sentence the noun is &amp;quot;scenery&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The noun &amp;#39;scenery&amp;#39; is an uncountable (mass) noun, it has no plural form.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So, &amp;#39;are&amp;#39; must replace &amp;#39;is&amp;#39; in this statement.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the sentence is grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The correct sentence should be:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The scenery of Kashmir is enchanting.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​&lt;strong&gt;Statement B:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;#39;Ethics&amp;#39; as a noun is considered a singular noun.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The verb form &amp;#39;deals&amp;#39; (singular) agrees with the noun (subject).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the statement is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Statement C:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;​&amp;#39;Applause&amp;#39; is a non-count noun that refers to inanimate objects.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So, it always takes a singular verb with it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The verb form (was) agrees with the subject in this sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hence, the statement is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Option 3,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Only B and C&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;A&amp;#39;, i.e. the error lies in this part of the sentence.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;The error lies in the incorrect usage of noun.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Furnitures&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;needs to be replaced with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;furniture&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Furniture is an uncountable noun and as per rule, &lt;strong&gt;uncountable nouns are never made plural with the help of &amp;#39;s/es&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence is:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;All the furniture have been&lt;/strong&gt; sent to the old office located in a to&lt;/em&gt;wn.&amp;#39;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Uncountable Noun:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;uncountable nouns are substances, concepts etc that we cannot divide into separate elements.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;त्रुटि &amp;nbsp;noun के गलत उपयोग में निहित है।&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;Furnitures&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; को &amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;furniture&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;से बदलने की जरूरत है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;फर्नीचर एक uncountable noun&amp;nbsp; है और नियम के अनुसार, &lt;strong&gt;uncountable nouns को कभी भी &amp;#39;s/es&amp;#39; की मदद से बहुवचन नहीं बनाया जाता है।&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;अत: सही उत्तर विकल्प 1 है।&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;called out.&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;The correct phrase should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;called off.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;called off&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;means to cancel or end something, which is appropriate in this context.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;called off the strike,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The workers &lt;strong&gt;called off the strike &lt;/strong&gt;because the management acceded to all their demands.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &amp;quot;all their demands,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;the management acceded to,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4: &amp;quot;The workers called out,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence contains the error and should be corrected to &amp;quot;called off.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here, the erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;who are.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the part &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;who are.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;are&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect because it does not agree with the singular subject&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;pet dog&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to &lt;b&gt;Subject-Verb agreement, &lt;/b&gt;a plural subject takes a plural verb and a singular subject takes a singular verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, we need a singular helping&amp;nbsp;verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;is&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; with the subject&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;pet dog.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct verb should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;is&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; to match the singular subject.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is Option 2.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;cke_bm_1138416S&quot; style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;Correct sentence&lt;span id=&quot;cke_bm_1138416E&quot; style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;em&gt;Janet has a pet dog &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;who is&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; very smart.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option B.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The error lies in the&lt;strong&gt; part 2 &lt;/strong&gt;of the question.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;He&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used instead of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;They&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;They&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is a plural pronoun while &amp;#39;A boy&amp;#39; is a singular Noun. So, according to this, we should use a singular Pronoun.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;So, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Option 2&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt; is:- &lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;When a boy enrolls in the university, &lt;strong&gt;he&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;should ensure his registration process is completed promptly to avoid any delays in starting his classes&amp;#39;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(C)​.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error is in &lt;strong&gt;part (C)&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;if I had seen her earlier&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; should replace &amp;#39;if I saw her earlier&amp;#39; to make the sentence grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected sentence is a &lt;strong&gt;third conditional&lt;/strong&gt;, which deals with hypothetical situations in the past that did not actually happen.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The third conditional is used to talk about unreal, or impossible events in the past. These are events that are &amp;quot;contrary to fact,&amp;quot; meaning they did not take place.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The third conditional is constructed using &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;if&amp;quot; + past perfect in the condition clause, and would/might/could + have + past participle in the result clause&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;If I had studied harder (unreal condition that didn&amp;#39;t happen), I would have passed the exam (unreal consequence of that condition).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similarly,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;If I had seen her earlier&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; - This is the if-clause (condition). We can tell this action did not happen, but we are imagining the possibility.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;I would have said something to her&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; - This is the result clause based on that unreal condition. It didn&amp;#39;t happen because the condition didn&amp;#39;t happen.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;I should have said something to her&amp;nbsp;if I had seen&amp;nbsp;her earlier.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;He had been improve&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the verb form used in the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;improve&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is not correctly conjugated in the &lt;strong&gt;past perfect continuous tense&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the past perfect continuous tense, the correct structure is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;subject + had been + present participle (verb + -ing)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the corrected part of the sentence should read:&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;He had been improving&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This construction indicates an ongoing action that had been happening in the past leading up to another past event or time.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrected sentence&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;He had been improving his communication skills in order to shine in his career.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;quot;option 1&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;option 1&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, we can use&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;commit&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;in place of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;committed&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make the sentence grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We always use 1st form of the&lt;strong&gt; main verb&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;) with &lt;strong&gt;helping verbs&lt;/strong&gt; like do, does, did, etc.,&amp;nbsp;and also with&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;modal verbs&lt;/strong&gt; like, will, shall, may, might, etc.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Due to the fact that they &lt;strong&gt;did&lt;/strong&gt; not &lt;strong&gt;read &lt;/strong&gt;English, the prisoners were unaware of what they were signing.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In the given sentence,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;did&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;is a &lt;strong&gt;helping verb &lt;/strong&gt;and we use&amp;nbsp;1st form of the&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;main verb&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;(&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;quot;commit&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;with the &lt;strong&gt;helping verb&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;did&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; instead of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;committed&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, we replace the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;main verb &amp;quot;committed&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;with the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;1st form of the&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;main verb&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;(&lt;strong&gt;V&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;commit&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make the sentence&amp;nbsp;grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All the other options are correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 1&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;We feel like we presented/ a case that showed through evidence and testimony/ &lt;strong&gt;that Mr. Rhodes did not &lt;u&gt;commit&lt;/u&gt;/ &lt;/strong&gt;the crime of seditious conspiracy,&amp;quot; Tarpley said.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The subject &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;it&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; requires the verb form &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;adopts&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; to agree in number and tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;a more egalitarian and inclusive attitude&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is correctly constructed and should remain unchanged.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Options 1 and 2 are grammatically incorrect because they either change the subject or use an inappropriate adjective form.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The Commonwealth remains a great platform for development aid, democratic values and educational opportunities, but its relevance is unlikely to increase &lt;strong&gt;unless it adopts a more&lt;/strong&gt; egalitarian and inclusive attitude.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A: &amp;quot;The Commonwealth remains a great platform for development aid, democratic values and educational opportunities,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B: &amp;quot;but its relevance is unlikely to increase,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(d)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, the use of the &lt;strong&gt;base form of the verb&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;b&gt;come&lt;/b&gt;&amp;#39; is &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The clause after &lt;strong&gt;Until or unless&lt;/strong&gt; does not posses &amp;quot;not&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence we have to &lt;strong&gt;remove &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;did not&amp;quot; and replace &lt;strong&gt;come &lt;/strong&gt;with &lt;strong&gt;came &lt;/strong&gt;to maintain the tense&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;past simple tense&lt;/span&gt;..&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;past tense form of the verb&lt;/span&gt; &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;came&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;should be used &lt;strong&gt;in place of&lt;/strong&gt; the &lt;strong&gt;base form of the verb &amp;#39;come&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;b&gt;Correct sentence:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;The husband asked his wife (a) to wait for him near the gate (b) until (c) he came back (d).&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;when I come&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The verb &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;come&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo; is in the present tense, which is incorrect after &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;when&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;After &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;when&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;, we use the past tense of the verb.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct form is &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;came&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence&lt;/strong&gt;: You were not at home &lt;strong&gt;when I came&lt;/strong&gt; to your house yesterday.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You were&lt;/strong&gt;: This is correct verb in the past tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Not at home&lt;/strong&gt;: This is a correct adverb phrase showing the location of the subject.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;To your house yesterday&lt;/strong&gt;: This is a correct prepositional phrase showing the destination and time of the action.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 2) i.e. Have&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct verb which agrees with the subject of the sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;have&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.✔️&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some countable nouns in English such as &lt;u&gt;&lt;em&gt;earnings, goods, odds, surroundings, proceeds, contents, and valuables&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/u&gt; only have a plural form and take a plural verb.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The earnings&lt;/strong&gt; for this quarter &lt;u&gt;exceed&lt;/u&gt; expectations&lt;/em&gt;. (with the subject &amp;#39;&lt;em&gt;earnings&lt;/em&gt;&amp;#39; we will use the plural &amp;#39;&lt;em&gt;exceed&lt;/em&gt;&amp;#39;)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, the whole statement is talking about a quality that exists to date and with the subject &amp;#39;&lt;em&gt;Locally produced goods&lt;/em&gt;&amp;#39; we will use &amp;#39;have&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The use of &amp;#39;&lt;u&gt;&lt;em&gt;has not&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&amp;#39; is incorrect as it is not a negative statement.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(77, 81, 86); &quot;&gt;❌&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(77, 81, 86); &quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(77, 81, 86); &quot;&gt;​&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Locally produced goods &lt;strong&gt;have&lt;/strong&gt; the advantage of shorter supply chains. This serves to be a major advantage for locally-made products, thereby increasing their competitiveness&lt;/em&gt;.✔️&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here, the erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Children were prohibited to attend.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The error is the use of the preposition&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;to&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;instead of&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;from.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the corrected version, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;prohibited from attending&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is the appropriate phrasing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct usage is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Children were prohibited from attending&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;instead of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Children were prohibited to attend.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;The sentence should be written as &lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Children were prohibited from attending&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; the military parade in which deadly weapons were displayed.&amp;#39;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is Option 1.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; correct answer &lt;/strong&gt;is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;No error&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;sentence is about&lt;/strong&gt; Saleem&amp;#39;s habit of switching off his mobile when situations are not to his liking.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Saleem has a tendency to switch&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is correctly constructed, with the phrase expressing a person&amp;#39;s habitual action.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The segment&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;off his mobile when things&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;provides the specifics of what Saleem tends to switch off.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;are not favourable for him&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; completes the sentence sensibly and grammatically with the situation when Saleem tends to switch off his mobile.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the sentence is &lt;strong&gt;grammatically correct&lt;/strong&gt; and makes logical sense. Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;No Error&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;He is as concerned as me&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The error in this sentence lies in the comparison being made.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;When making comparisons, especially with the verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to be&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; the subjective pronoun form should be used rather than the objective pronoun form.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;This is because both subjects are performing the action of the verb (being concerned in this case).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;me&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; should be replaced with &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;I&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to correctly construct the comparison, making the correct phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;He is as concerned as I&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;He is as concerned as I&lt;/strong&gt; regarding the renewed examination schedule.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Segments 1) &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;the renewed&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; 2) &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;examination schedule&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; and 3) &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;regarding&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; do not contain grammatical errors. They are correctly used in the context of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;The renewed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; correctly modifies &amp;quot;examination schedule,&amp;quot; indicating that the schedule has been updated or changed.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Regarding&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is the correct preposition to introduce the topic of concern, which in this case is the examination schedule.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The error in option 2 is the use of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;were&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; which should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;was&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;because the subject &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;a punishment of five years&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is singular.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Verb will be as per the subject &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;a punishment&amp;rsquo; &lt;/strong&gt;to ensure verb-subject agreement.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence is-&lt;strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The judge decided that the defendant was guilty of all charges, and that a punishment of five years in prison was appropriate.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1 (&amp;quot;the defendant was guilty of all charges,&amp;quot;) &lt;/strong&gt;is grammatically correct because it correctly states the decision made about the defendant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3 (&amp;quot;and that a punishment of five years&amp;quot;) &lt;/strong&gt;correctly connects two clauses with &amp;quot;and&amp;quot; and introduces the second decision.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4 (&amp;quot;The judge decided that&amp;quot;)&lt;/strong&gt; appropriately sets the scene for the actions decided by the judge.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
